  "prompt": "Why does Ben Affleck\u2019s Batman Kill people intentionally?",
  "response": "The portrayal of Batman in the DC Extended Universe (DCEU), specifically as portrayed by Ben Affleck, has been controversial due to his willingness to kill. This deviates from the traditional depiction of Batman, who adheres to a strict no-kill rule.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why the DCEU's Batman killed, according to the filmmakers and the context of the films:\n\n*   **A Broken and Jaded Batman:** The DCEU's Batman is older, more experienced, and deeply scarred by years of fighting crime and witnessing loss, including the death of Robin. This has left him disillusioned and believing that traditional methods are no longer effective. He's more brutal and willing to use lethal force as a means to an end.\n\n*   **The Influence of Frank Miller's \"The Dark Knight Returns\":** Director Zack Snyder drew inspiration from Frank Miller's \"The Dark Knight Returns,\" a comic book series that portrays an older, more ruthless Batman. This version of Batman is more willing to use lethal force, especially against criminals he deems irredeemable.\n\n*   **Desperation and the Threat of Superman:** In \"Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice,\" Batman sees Superman as an existential threat to humanity. He believes Superman's unchecked power could lead to widespread destruction. His desperation to stop Superman pushes him to cross lines he wouldn't normally cross.\n\n*   **The Nature of the Enemies:** In some instances, Batman's actions are portrayed as being in self-defense or against non-human threats. While some argue this doesn't excuse killing, the filmmakers have suggested that the context is important.\n\nIt's important to note that this interpretation of Batman has been divisive among fans, with some arguing that it betrays the core principles of the character, while others find it to be a compelling and realistic portrayal of a hero pushed to his limits.",
